Noticed delay too large so set filter, will investigate why later

maindf <- read.csv(file = '/Users/benlinden/Documents/Documents/R/TfL Delays/2017-tfl-delays.csv')

colnames(maindf) <- c('Date','Time','Delay','Line')

maindf_filt <- filter(maindf, Delay < 100)

maindf_filt$date_and_time <- paste(maindf_filt$Date, maindf_filt$Time)

maindf_filt$date_and_time <- as.POSIXct(maindf_filt$date_and_time, format = "%d/%m/%Y %H:%M")

head(maindf_filt)

Explore change in mean when filtering

change_in_df <- data.frame(mean_df$Line, (mean_df$Delay - mean_df_filt$Delay))

colnames(change_in_df) <- c('Line','Delay')

ggplot(change_in_df,aes(x=Line, y=Delay, stat="Identity", fill=as.factor(Line))) +
  geom_histogram(stat="identity") +
  ylab('Change in Average Delay') +
  labs(x="Line",y="Change in Average Delay",fill="Line",title="Average Delay on TfL Tube Lines (2017")
## Warning: Ignoring unknown parameters: binwidth, bins, pad

Can tell from this that Hammersmith & City and Waterloo & City experienced most change and therefore had huge delays > 100 mins. This could be due to the fact that a lower number of trains operate on this line.

Therefore remove from analysis.
